BUGS already reported:

When I issue the "counts" command to BackEnd (processing the lislook
example database), I get a segmentation fault, even if "counts" is the
first command I enter.

I was confused by messages like this:
  Enter your command ('help' for help): searchlocal f_empty:a
  Expression is not a pointer
which you explained meant that a's type is an unconstrained type variable.
I thought it had something to do with the type of variable "a" in the
underlying program -- "int" rather than "int*".  I don't even know what
"pointer" means in this context, since I think it doesn't have to do with
whether the variable is a pointer (I can produce that message for both
"int" and "int*" variables).  It would be helpful to users if you made the
message a bit more explicit.

[For foo.c, described in my mail of Fri, 9 Apr 1999 10:18:52:]
Enter your command ('help' for help): searchlocal f:*a
../../src/globalInf/cTypeTable.c:1238: failed assertion `0 <= componentNum && componentNum < getCTypeArity(t)'
Abort

Please add a flag to searchlocal to report all hits, even if no operator is
involved.

